supercat@MCS.COM (John Payson) writes:

>avoid letting enemy knowledge of the old weaken the new).  Note also
>that compression by itself is cryptographically very poor.  Even if
>one were to use, e.g., dynamic huffman encoding with a passphrase-set
>initialization tree, patterns would still be highly visible [they'd
>change fairly frequently, but the changes would be easy to spot].
>While there's no harm in compressing data before encrypting it, one
>should not assume that compression does anything for cryptographic
>strength.

But if there are any obvious patterns, then there is still compression
to be done, correct? An "optimally" compressed file would appear "optimally"
random, wouldn't it?

